have been given as a nickname to blacksmiths.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): presumably an adoption of the German surname."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Weyland IV was born in 1335, in Baylham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert de Weyland, was 36 and his mother, Cecily de Baldock, was 23. He married Margaret de Burnaville. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1364, in his hometown, at the age of 29."},"et":{"1335–1364":"1335–1364","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1324–Female":"1324–Surnud","1324–Male":"1324–Surnud","1334–1377":"1334–1377","1338–Female":"1338–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1346–1416":"1346–1416","1340–Female":"1340–Surnud","1363–1389":"1363–1389","1300–1345":"1300–1345","1312–1350":"1312–1350","1363":"1363","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1338":"1338","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1324":"1324","1345":"1345","1312":"1312","1389":"1389","1334":"1334","1300":"1300","1377":"1377","1364":"1364","1320":"1320","about 1363":"umbes 1363","1416":"1416","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Baylham, Suffolk, England":"Baylham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Charsfield, Suffolk, England":"Charsfield, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1335–1364":"1335–1364","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut"